post_text:
Attention Summer School Parents:

Summer school will begin Monday, July 6th at 7:30 a.m and dismiss at 2:30 p.m. We are running 3 bus routes and they will be leaving the school at approximately 6:20 a.m.

A staff member will be riding each bus every morning to take the temperature of each child. Any child that doesn’t ride the bus will need to report to the Elementary office every morning to be checked for a temperature before going to class. We are taking additional precautions to ensure the safety of all students and staff members.

Your child will not be allowed to attend school if they have:
Temperature of 100.4 F or higher
Frequent unexplained cough
Unexplained shortness of breath or difficulty breathing
Unexplained tiredness

All Elementary and Middle School students are welcome to attend even if not pre-registered. Please contact the Elementary Office if you have any questions or concerns.

shared_text:
Oregon County Health Department
May 11 at 5:17 PM ·

Oregon County Health Department is now taking appointments for back to school immunizations for the 2020-2021 school year. This is a little different, as we usually do not require appointments. Waiting until the end of summer when appointment slots are already full may mean missed class time for an appointment after the start of the school year. We are also spacing immunization appointments out through May and June, due to the COVID 19 pandemic, to decrease waiting room congestion.
Students entering kindergarten will be required to be up to date on their Dtap, Polio, MMR and Varicella. Eighth graders need to have a current Tdap and Meningococcal and Twelfth graders will also need a Meningococcal booster depending on the age they were with their previous dose.
For an appointment or questions regarding vaccinations or Missouri requirements, please call 417-778-7450 for ALTON or 417-264-3114 for a Tuesday or a Wednesday appointment at THAYER. We do ask that you bring a current immunization record to your appointment.

post_text: Governor Parson has ordered school closed in Missouri for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. We will send out additional information in the next few days regarding this order.
shared_text:
Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education
April 9 at 3:12 PM ·

Missouri Governor Mike Parson announced in the Thursday, April 9 press briefing that Missouri schools will remain closed through this school year. DESE, along with several school superintendents from across the state, made the recommendation to Governor Mike Parson on April 9. Learn more about this announcement here in remarks by Commissioner of Education Margie Vandeven.

https://dese.mo.gov/sites/default/files/Gov-Closes-Schools-April-9.pdf

post_text: In March the sophomores had the opportunity to tour South Central Career Center. Juniors and seniors have the opportunity to attend for 2 years and earn certification in the class they attend. Students need to have a 2.5 GPA, be on track to graduate, and have good attendance. If you are a current sophomore, meet these requirements, and wish to apply, email Mrs.Johnson at johnsonj@koshk12.org. If you meet the requirements,then I will provide you with directions to complete an application from SCCC. Applications are accepted on a first come,first served basis so the sooner you contact me the better! Thank you!

"Saying NO to drugs shows character."

Dress like your favorite character day

"Saying NO to drugs shows character."

Dress like your favorite character day

post_text:
Red Ribbon Week 2019

October 28-31

Red Ribbon Week is used as a way of taking a stand for our hopes and dreams through making a commitment of saying “no” to drugs and alcohol. Each student is invited to participate in a week of spirit to celebrate our choice to be drug free.

Monday- Saying “NO” to drugs shows character.- Dress like your favorite TV or Book character.

Tuesday- Don’t get mixed up on drugs!- Teachers dress like students and students dress like teachers!

Wednesday-Drugs are old school.-Dress like your favorite decade!

Thursday- Hocus Pocus keep your dreams in focus. Dress like your future career.

Friday- NO SCHOOL

post_text: Koshkonong FCCLA had two projects taken to the FCCLA Region 9 Star Event competition held in West Plains today. Both teams received a Gold medal, which sends them on to compete at the State Star Events at Tan-Tar-A in March. Sooo proud of these fine young man and women!! Pictured in back is Austin Woods, Destini Clark, and Mary Beth Thompson, presented on Chapter Service Project display. In front, Bobbi Busbey and Abigail Braswell, presented on Advocacy portfolio.
